T1  - Nonergodic Economic Growth
PY  - 1993
Y1  - 1993/04/01
DO  - 10.2307/2298061
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 60
IS  - 2
SP  - 349
EP  - 366
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper explores the role of complementarities and incomplete markets in economic growth. We analyze the evolution of an economy composed of a countable set of industries. Individual industries exhibit non-convexities in production and are linked by localized technological complementarities. These complementarities, when strong enough, produce multiple equilibria in long-run economic activity. The equilibria have a simple probabilistic structure that demonstrates how local interactions can affect the aggregate equilibrium. The model generates interesting cross-sectional and intertemporal dynamics as coordination problems become the source of aggregate and individual industry volatility. The model also illustrates how the growth of leading sectors can cause a takeoff to a high aggregate production equilibrium.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2298061
ER  - 



